  "body": "### Overview\r\nCurrently, `project.load` raises a `ProjectAlreadyLoaded` error when you try to load a project from a path which already has a loaded project.\r\n\r\nThis makes it inconvenient to use directly in Python code.\r\n\r\nIt would be preferable if the following code ran without errors:\r\n```\r\nfrom brownie import project\r\nproject_path = \"<path>\"\r\nproject_1 = project.load(project_path)\r\nproject_2 = project.load(project_path)\r\nassert project_1 is project_2\r\n```\r\n\r\nI am not sure if there are use cases where it may make sense for a user to force a reload (rebuild) of a project. If there are such cases, we could add a `force` keyword argument to make the following code run without errors:\r\n```\r\nfrom brownie import project\r\nproject_path = \"<path>\"\r\nproject_1 = project.load(project_path)\r\nproject_2 = project.load(project_path, force=True)\r\nassert project_1 is not project_2\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Dependencies\r\nInclude links to any open issues that must be resolved before this feature can be implemented.\r\n",
